  1. Calculate the mean, variance, and standard deviation for the variable mpg and assign them into variable names m, v, and s. Report the results in the print statement.
# Enter your code here!
m <- mean(mtcars$mpg)
v <- var(mtcars$mpg)
s <- sd(mtcars$mpg)

Question 2

Use different visualization tools to summarize the data sets in this question.

  1. Using the PlantGrowth data set, visualize and compare the weight of the plant in the three separated group. Give labels to the title, x-axis, and y-axis on the graph. Write a paragraph to summarize your findings.
# Load the data set
data("PlantGrowth")

# Head of the data set
head(PlantGrowth)
# Enter your code here!
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight, fill = group)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Weight for Different Groups",
       x = "Group",
       y = "Weight")

Result:

=> Report a paragraph to summarize your findings from the plot!

treatment 1 has a negative effect on weight of plants while treatment 2 has a positive effect on the weight of plants. The weight of the control group was 50 while treatment 1 was around 45 and treatment 2 was around 55

# Head of the cleaned data set
head(housingData)
# Enter your code here!
housingData %>% 
  group_by(Boro) %>%
